Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Chop the @British Turkey Steaks{2} into 2cm chunks. When hot, add the turkey to the pan along with a pinch of @salt{} and fry until starting to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Lower the heat to medium sprinkle over the @Shawarma Spice Mix{1} and fry for another ~{2-3%minutes}, until the turkey is cooked. IMPORTANT: The turkey is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Transfer to a #bowl{} (keep the pan!).

While the turkey cooks, halve, peel and finely slice the @Echalion Shallot{1}. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1}(peeled) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @Bell Pepper{1} and @Green Pepper{1} and discard the cores and seeds. Chop into small pieces. Halve the @Green Chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Boil your #kettle{}.

When the turkey is out, wipe out the pan, keep on medium heat and add another drizzle of @oil{}. Pop in the shallot and peppers. Cook, stirring occasionally, until starting to soften, then add the garlic and a pinch of @chilli{} (use as much as you like - you can always add more later!). Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the @Freekeh{100}. Cook for another ~{1%minute}. Meanwhile, combine the boiling @Water{200%ml} and @Vegetable Stock Powder{1} in a #measuring jug{}.

Stir the stock into the pan then cover tightly with a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) and leave to cook on a medium-low heat for ~{15%minutes}. TIP: Don't be tempted to remove the lid in this time! When the 15 mins is up, remove the pan from the heat, lift the lid and pop the @Baby Spinach{125} and cooked turkey (along with any juices) on top. Quickly replace the lid and leave to one side for ~{5%minutes}.

As the pilaf cooks, zest the @Lemon{1} then chop into wedges. Roughly chop the @Flat Leaf Parsley{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Pick the @Mint{1}(roughly chopped leaves only) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Pop the @Low Fat Natural Yoghurt{75} into a small bowl and stir through a quarter of the parsley and mint.

Remove the lid from the pan and stir the spinach and turkey through the pilaf. Add the remaining parsley and mint and the lemon zest. Stir together then season to taste with @salt{}, @pepper{}, a squeeze of lemon juice and a pinch more chilli (if needed). Serve the turkey pilaf in #bowls{} topped with the herby yoghurt and any remaining lemon wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!